 <H1>Third Normal Form  (3NF)</H1> 
 <P><UL>
<LI><H2>Reln R with FDs F is in 3NF if, for all X      A  in
</H2>
<UL>
<LI>A      X   (called a trivial FD), or
<LI>X contains a key for R, or
<LI>A is part of some key for R.  
</UL></UL><UL>
<LI><H2>Minimality of a key is crucial in third condition above!  
</H2>
</UL><UL>
<LI><H2>If R is in BCNF, obviously in 3NF.
</H2>
</UL><UL>
<LI><H2>If R is in 3NF, some redundancy is possible.  It is a compromise, used when BCNF not achievable (e.g., no ``good’’ decomp, or performance considerations).
</H2>
</UL><UL>
<LI><H2>Lossless-join, dependency-preserving decomposition of R into a collection of 3NF relations always possible.</H2>
</UL></P>
